properties.location: the King River at Docker Road
properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the King River at Docker Road.

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOCKER RD BRIDGE

Since 9 am Monday, rainfall totals of 5-15 mm have been recorded in the King River catchment. No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Tuesday.

Minor flooding is occurring along the King River in response to the rainfall. River levels along the King River will remain elevated for the next few days.

King River:
Minor flooding is occurring along the King River.

The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is currently peaking around 3.84 metres, with minor flooding. The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is likely to remain above the minor flood level (3.70 m) during Tuesday.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 21/06/2023 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Glenelg River to Casterton.

MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT CASTERTON TUESDAY EVENING

  • In the 24 hours to 9 am Tuesday, rainfall totals of up to 6 mm have been recorded across the Glenelg River catchment and river levels are elevated in response to recent rainfall.
  • River levels are nearing the minor flood level at Dergholm, while a peak around the minor flood level is possible at Casterton during Tuesday evening.
  • No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Tuesday. Showers are forecast for Wednesday and into Thursday.
Glenelg River to Casterton:

  • Minor flooding may occur along the Glenelg River to Casterton.
  • The Glenelg River at Casterton is currently at 3.22 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. The Glenelg River at Casterton may peak near the minor flood level (3.80 metres) Tuesday evening.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

River levels are elevated along the Kiewa River in response to the rainfall. Minor flooding is expected at Bandiana Tuesday morning.

No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Tuesday.

Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge:
Minor flooding is expected along the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is currently at 2.90 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is likely to remain below the minor flood level (3.30 m) during Tuesday.

The Kiewa River at Bandiana is currently at 2.79 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. The Kiewa River at Bandiana is expected to exceed the minor flood level (2.80 m) Tuesday morning.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Sevens & Castle Creeks at Euroa.

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT EUROA

In the 24 hours to 9 am Tuesday, rainfall totals of 5-15 mm have been recorded in the Seven and Castle Creeks catchment.

Minor flooding is approaching a peak at Euroa Tuesday morning. Isolated showers are forecast for the remainder of Tuesday.

Castle Creek:
River levels are easing along the Castle Creek at Telfords Bridge.

Seven Creeks to Euroa:
Minor flooding is occurring along the Seven Creeks to Euroa.

The Seven Creeks at Euroa is currently at 2.53 metres and rising, above the minor flood level. The Seven Creeks at Euroa may peak near 2.80 metres Tuesday afternoon, with minor flooding.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Local flooding in streets and along overland flow paths is likely if there is local rain
  • The Caravan Park, Rotary Park, land opposite the Memorial Oval and the Bowls Club may begin to be inundated
